knowledge_graph.title: Baked potato
knowledge_graph.description: A baked potato, known in some parts of the United Kingdom as a jacket potato, is a preparation of potato originating from South America, specifically Peru. It may be served with fillings, toppings or condiments such as butter, cheese, sour cream, gravy, baked beans, and tuna, among others.

related_questions.snippet: How long to bake a potato at 400 degrees? It takes about 1 hour to bake a potato in the oven at 400 degrees. Scrub the potatoes clean, poke holes with a fork, and rub with oil, salt, and pepper if desired.

related_questions.question: Should you wrap baked potatoes in foil?
related_questions.snippet: "I see a lot of people using foil to wrap their potatoes in but this is a big no-no and causes soggy skins!" he says. Foil holds in moisture and steams the potatoes, resulting in a "boiled" taste and texture. Plus, without the use of foil, the skin will get extra crispy and flavorful.

related_questions.question: What is the best temperature and time to bake a potato?
related_questions.snippet: Bake the potatoes for about 50 to 60 minutes at 425°F (220°C) until completely soft when pierced. That's it! This method will give you the best baked potatoes that are crispy on the outside and fluffy in the middle.

buttons.snippet: We recommend baking potatoes at 400 degrees F for about an hour. Smaller spuds might take a little less time, while larger baking potatoes over 1 pound might take a little more. For a fully baked Idaho Russet Burbank, the internal temperature should be right at 210 degrees F.
